12. oblivio looks much more like an ablative than a nominative: and is better taken as the former case, although it is true that the singular form oblivium is nowhere else found, and even the plural generally in poetry. Madvig and Nipperdey would read oblivione.

meminissent: some remembered Helvidius' proposal— by which Vespasian would only have played a secondary part in the restoration —and informed the emperor of it.
